261
00:17:15,582 --> 00:17:17,742
Where on earth is it?

262
00:17:34,052 --> 00:17:35,912
This is my father's cabin.

263
00:17:35,912 --> 00:17:37,412
I was on the way to find the keepsake from my father...

264
00:17:37,412 --> 00:17:38,912
which I lost while carrying you.

265
00:17:38,912 --> 00:17:41,482
I'm taking a shovel because I'm worried it might've been buried.

266
00:17:45,312 --> 00:17:46,942
Assistant?

267
00:17:47,382 --> 00:17:50,642
Yes. I'm writing a new novel,

268
00:17:50,642 --> 00:17:52,282
and I need someone to help me.

269
00:17:54,182 --> 00:17:55,882
But why me?

270
00:17:56,282 --> 00:17:57,642
I am not a writer.

271
00:17:58,012 --> 00:18:02,052
The person I need is not a writer but a vet.

272
00:18:02,812 --> 00:18:05,482
Why do you need a vet when you write?

273
00:18:08,242 --> 00:18:10,112
Do you want me to be Baek Seol's butler?

274
00:18:10,582 --> 00:18:14,212
No. I need knowledge in veterinary medicine.

275
00:18:14,212 --> 00:18:18,942
So you can be my advisor, supervisor, and assistant.

276
00:18:20,412 --> 00:18:23,412
What do you think? I'll pay you well.

277
00:18:23,412 --> 00:18:24,912
No.

278
00:18:24,912 --> 00:18:27,052
I quit being a vet a long time ago.

279
00:18:27,112 --> 00:18:29,552
I will recommend you someone good.

280
00:18:29,552 --> 00:18:30,912
I don't want anyone else.

281
00:18:31,312 --> 00:18:33,642
I want you to do that.

282
00:18:34,182 --> 00:18:37,412
No. It can't be me.

283
00:18:40,382 --> 00:18:42,942
Why did you quit being a vet?

284
00:18:43,912 --> 00:18:46,482
Is there a great story about it?

285
00:18:48,382 --> 00:18:50,482
I'll tell you later when we become close.

286
00:18:52,412 --> 00:18:54,782
Let's be close then, start now.

287
00:18:56,382 --> 00:18:59,112
From the moment I saw you, I've been wanting to be close to you.

288
00:19:06,912 --> 00:19:09,312
Excuse me. Get me another pint.

289
00:19:15,642 --> 00:19:17,182
"Silence of the Lambs".

290
00:19:22,812 --> 00:19:25,242
"Silence of the Lambs"?

291
00:19:26,912 --> 00:19:28,812
For me, it's "Silence of the Cows".

292
00:19:32,282 --> 00:19:33,942
"Silence of the Cows".

293
00:19:38,312 --> 00:19:39,582
Do you remember the time...

294
00:19:39,582 --> 00:19:41,442
when the foot-and-mouth disease was very serious several years ago?

295
00:19:41,812 --> 00:19:44,312
But it happened many times.

296
00:19:46,182 --> 00:19:49,552
Anyway, when that happened, they didn't have enough hands,

297
00:19:49,552 --> 00:19:52,482
so vets and even students were mobilized to stop it.

298
00:19:53,482 --> 00:19:54,742
Even you?

299
00:19:56,312 --> 00:20:00,412
I was in charge of euthanasia and collecting blood samples for tests.

300
00:20:01,942 --> 00:20:03,012
Oh, dear.

301
00:20:04,112 --> 00:20:05,812
The farmers...

302
00:20:06,552 --> 00:20:10,312
fed the cows the most expensive feed and cried.

303
00:20:11,642 --> 00:20:14,182
Beside them, I counted the number of syringes.

304
00:20:15,682 --> 00:20:17,942
A very young calf...

305
00:20:18,212 --> 00:20:21,842
licked my hand when I was there to kill him.

306
00:20:25,112 --> 00:20:26,742
When I euthanized him,

307
00:20:27,842 --> 00:20:30,812
he died in just three seconds because he was too young.

308
00:20:34,112 --> 00:20:37,712
Ever since that, I can't forget about the cows' cries.

309
00:20:39,912 --> 00:20:43,012
I became a vet to treat sick animals.

310
00:20:45,842 --> 00:20:49,642
But I killed more animals than I saved.

311
00:20:52,212 --> 00:20:53,712
So I ran away.

312
00:20:54,552 --> 00:20:57,812
I ran away because the cows didn't stop crying.

313
00:20:59,182 --> 00:21:00,612
That's my story.

314
00:21:03,112 --> 00:21:04,782
We'd like to order some more beer.

315
00:21:07,742 --> 00:21:09,482
Now that think of it,

316
00:21:10,052 --> 00:21:14,582
whenever I aim to do something related to killing, I'm frustrated.

317
00:21:15,682 --> 00:21:17,552
Maybe I was a butcher in my past life.

318
00:21:18,512 --> 00:21:21,842
Or maybe I killed someone.

319
00:21:22,782 --> 00:21:24,112
(Sungsoocheong)

320
00:21:24,112 --> 00:21:27,682
Maybe I'm being punished from killing someone...

321
00:21:28,642 --> 00:21:30,612
whom I shouldn't have killed.

322
00:22:18,482 --> 00:22:19,842
Why are you here?

323
00:22:33,235 --> 00:22:34,605
Why are you here?

324
00:22:36,535 --> 00:22:39,505
What brings you here?

325
00:22:41,335 --> 00:22:42,805
Are you here to see a fortuneteller?

326
00:22:42,805 --> 00:22:44,875
I asked you first.

327
00:22:51,135 --> 00:22:52,235
Who are you?

328
00:22:52,935 --> 00:22:55,105
Why do you keep loitering around here?

329
00:23:02,305 --> 00:23:05,935
I fell in love at first sight.

330
00:23:12,635 --> 00:23:14,105
Do you want to die?

331
00:23:14,375 --> 00:23:16,035
Not with you.

332
00:23:18,375 --> 00:23:19,705
I'm talking about Jeon Seol.

333
00:23:25,905 --> 00:23:27,405
What are you doing out here?

334
00:23:27,505 --> 00:23:30,935
You're not supposed to leave laundries out. They'll get wet.

335
00:23:31,405 --> 00:23:33,575
I was going to take them now.

336
00:23:33,705 --> 00:23:35,475
I'll take care of it. You can go in.

337
00:23:38,235 --> 00:23:40,235
- What's wrong? - Bang Jin.

338
00:23:41,375 --> 00:23:44,005
- Ma Bang Jin. - Why?

339
00:23:44,075 --> 00:23:47,005
I was on a roll with my writing just now.

340
00:23:47,205 --> 00:23:49,405
Go to the kitchen and bring a bowl of red beans.

341
00:23:50,075 --> 00:23:51,405
Why red beans?

342
00:23:51,675 --> 00:23:54,135
I can sense something evil coming.

343
00:23:56,105 --> 00:23:58,105
There are two,

344
00:24:00,335 --> 00:24:02,075
but I'm not sure which one.

345
00:24:03,735 --> 00:24:06,135
Which one is it?

346
00:24:12,805 --> 00:24:14,535
Gosh, my eyes hurt.

347
00:24:15,675 --> 00:24:16,805
What are you doing?

348
00:24:16,805 --> 00:24:18,135
- Go get the red beans. - Goodness.

349
00:24:21,605 --> 00:24:23,405
How and where...

350
00:24:23,405 --> 00:24:26,535
did you get to know that girl?

351
00:24:26,805 --> 00:24:30,335
When I arrived in Korea from the US,

352
00:24:31,305 --> 00:24:32,335
I fell in love at first sight at the airport.

353
00:24:35,805 --> 00:24:36,935
"The US"?

354
00:24:37,805 --> 00:24:40,805
"The US". That sounds good.

355
00:24:41,605 --> 00:24:44,205
Stop lying all the time.

356
00:24:45,175 --> 00:24:49,935
Are New Yorkers all old-fashioned like this these days?

357
00:24:53,235 --> 00:24:56,575
Something is coming. We've got to run away.

358
00:24:56,705 --> 00:24:59,375
Hey, where are you going?

359
00:25:00,335 --> 00:25:03,505
- Go away! Go away! - My goodness!

360
00:25:04,375 --> 00:25:06,175
It hurts!

361
00:25:06,275 --> 00:25:08,035
- Go away! - Gosh, it hurts.

362
00:25:08,335 --> 00:25:09,475
Mr. Han!

363
00:25:13,675 --> 00:25:14,905
Han Se Ju?

364
00:25:19,135 --> 00:25:20,605
Are you crazy?

365
00:25:23,475 --> 00:25:25,075
Mr. Han. What brings you here?

366
00:25:26,005 --> 00:25:27,975
Are you here to meet me?

367
00:25:30,105 --> 00:25:33,605
That's ridiculous. I'm not here to meet you.

368
00:25:36,575 --> 00:25:39,275
Mr. Han. Mr. Han.

369
00:25:40,735 --> 00:25:42,675
Gosh. Go in.

370
00:25:43,075 --> 00:25:46,235
- My goodness! - What have you done!

371
00:25:46,905 --> 00:25:48,635
There's nothing evil.

372
00:25:53,775 --> 00:25:55,035
What's wrong?

373
00:25:56,075 --> 00:25:57,375
Do you really see something?

374
00:25:57,375 --> 00:26:00,675
I can see it all over his face.

375
00:26:02,635 --> 00:26:03,705
What do you mean?

376
00:26:04,805 --> 00:26:06,175
I can see he's handsome.

377
00:26:06,275 --> 00:26:08,575
Goodness. Are you kidding me?

378
00:26:08,575 --> 00:26:11,205
Go pick the red beans. They're domestic product.

379
00:26:17,975 --> 00:26:20,875
People can stumble over it.

380
00:26:21,575 --> 00:26:25,505
She might've lost the fortunetelling skill, but not her throwing skill.

381
00:26:26,035 --> 00:26:29,375
What a technical movement it was.

382
00:26:33,905 --> 00:26:35,205
Thank...

383
00:26:48,005 --> 00:26:49,805
you.

384
00:26:53,505 --> 00:26:54,875
My goodness.

385
00:27:04,805 --> 00:27:06,705
He's so gentle.

386
00:27:07,675 --> 00:27:08,935
And...

387
00:27:09,935 --> 00:27:11,105
here is some more.

388
00:27:16,105 --> 00:27:17,575
Hearts.

389
00:27:20,335 --> 00:27:23,135
They're not hearts. They're red beans.

390
00:27:27,235 --> 00:27:28,805
I see.

391
00:27:29,605 --> 00:27:32,005
- Goodbye. - Excuse me.

392
00:27:33,375 --> 00:27:34,805
What's your name?

393
00:27:37,575 --> 00:27:40,305
I can't reveal my name for some reason.

394
00:27:42,935 --> 00:27:46,075
You can just call me "Yoo".

395
00:28:13,575 --> 00:28:14,705
Mr. Han.

396
00:28:15,805 --> 00:28:17,875
Hold on a second, Mr. Han.

397
00:28:19,235 --> 00:28:20,235
Mr. Han.

398
00:28:20,435 --> 00:28:21,935
Do you know Yoo Jin Oh?

399
00:28:23,075 --> 00:28:25,275
How do you know him? What did he say to you?

400
00:28:25,575 --> 00:28:26,575
Did he talk about me?

401
00:28:26,875 --> 00:28:28,375
To which question should I answer first?

402
00:28:28,375 --> 00:28:31,235
All of them. One by one. Sincerely.

403
00:28:32,035 --> 00:28:33,875
First, I don't know Yoo Jin Oh.

404
00:28:33,875 --> 00:28:36,335
Therefore, I don't need to answer the rest.

405
00:28:38,075 --> 00:28:39,205
Fine.

406
00:28:41,735 --> 00:28:43,435
Is that why you came?

407
00:28:53,935 --> 00:28:55,035
What's this?

408
00:28:57,635 --> 00:29:00,275
- How did you... - I found it on the street.

409
00:29:00,935 --> 00:29:01,935
Are you happy now?

410
00:29:05,805 --> 00:29:09,205
Goodness. Did you just act cold while being nice?

411
00:29:09,405 --> 00:29:12,605
Where did you learn such a line? From the internet?

412
00:29:13,505 --> 00:29:15,075
Stop following me.

413
00:29:15,975 --> 00:29:18,275
Did you go back to the cabin to find this?

414
00:29:18,475 --> 00:29:21,535
Because of me? For me? You didn't want me to be sad?

415
00:29:21,605 --> 00:29:22,635
Hey.

416
00:29:23,105 --> 00:29:25,675
You're totally misunderstanding.

417
00:29:26,305 --> 00:29:28,805
I just went out on business...

418
00:29:29,605 --> 00:29:33,375
and there was a thick fog. So I stopped the car.

419
00:29:34,105 --> 00:29:35,375
Then I found something shiny.

420
00:29:36,635 --> 00:29:37,805
Forget it.

421
00:29:39,575 --> 00:29:43,275
You went out and went to the cabin because you were thinking of me.

422
00:29:43,335 --> 00:29:47,475
Due to a thick fog, you stopped the car and found something shiny.

423
00:29:47,475 --> 00:29:48,605
And it was this pocket watch.

424
00:29:48,605 --> 00:29:51,205
What you said with the messy wording sounds about right...

425
00:29:51,205 --> 00:29:54,935
except the part that goes, "I was thinking of you."

426
00:29:55,605 --> 00:29:58,775
You don't have to exclude that part. It doesn't sound so wrong.

427
00:29:58,935 --> 00:30:00,405
It sounds wrong.

428
00:30:00,405 --> 00:30:02,805
It sounds so wrong because it's not true.

429
00:30:05,005 --> 00:30:07,035
Let's go. I'll treat you to something delicious.

430
00:30:07,035 --> 00:30:08,905
I want to thank you for finding my heart.

431
00:30:16,505 --> 00:30:19,005
Will you really be okay with this?

432
00:30:20,305 --> 00:30:22,275
What's wrong with this? I like this place.

433
00:30:23,105 --> 00:30:24,505
Are you sure about that?

434
00:30:25,005 --> 00:30:26,035
Why do you ask?

435
00:30:26,975 --> 00:30:30,035
I did say that I don't want to go back to those days 10 years ago...

436
00:30:30,035 --> 00:30:31,205
because it was like a nightmare.

437
00:30:32,705 --> 00:30:34,035
Is it because of that?

438
00:30:34,805 --> 00:30:36,075
Do you remember now?

439
00:30:36,075 --> 00:30:38,175
Yes, the memories came back.

440
00:30:39,235 --> 00:30:42,005
The part-timer who used to bring me hot chocolate.

441
00:30:42,535 --> 00:30:43,975
The crazy fan who used to take my photos.

442
00:30:45,775 --> 00:30:47,205
Don't call me like that.

443
00:30:48,435 --> 00:30:50,975
What do you even know about me besides what I look like?

444
00:30:51,205 --> 00:30:52,905
I might know some things about you.

445
00:30:53,305 --> 00:30:55,575
Writers speak through their writings, you know.

446
00:30:55,575 --> 00:30:57,405
I was a no-name writer back then.

447
00:30:59,305 --> 00:31:02,335
Actually, I read it.

448
00:31:02,975 --> 00:31:04,275
The manuscript.

449
00:31:25,775 --> 00:31:26,775
Are you closing now?

450
00:31:26,775 --> 00:31:29,175
Oh, we'll be closing in 30 minutes.

451
00:31:29,375 --> 00:31:30,575
You can take your time.

452
00:31:31,075 --> 00:31:33,105
Okay, thank you.

453
00:31:46,735 --> 00:31:49,805
It sure is like "Misery". You're like that woman in "Misery".

454
00:31:50,335 --> 00:31:53,175
Don't say that. I'm your first fan.

455
00:31:53,775 --> 00:31:57,005
So? You think you got to know me through what you read?

456
00:31:57,035 --> 00:31:59,075
Just from a piece of paper that was chucked away,

457
00:31:59,905 --> 00:32:01,805
- you think you know me? - We had conversations too.

458
00:32:01,805 --> 00:32:03,235
We had conversations?

459
00:32:03,975 --> 00:32:04,975
I did?

460
00:32:05,475 --> 00:32:06,475
With you?

461
00:32:09,075 --> 00:32:10,105
This is for you.

462
00:32:11,305 --> 00:32:13,105
I hope you had a great day.

463
00:32:18,805 --> 00:32:20,035
Are you a writer?

464
00:32:22,135 --> 00:32:24,105
At the moment, I'm just an aspiring writer.

465
00:32:24,335 --> 00:32:26,235
Do you enjoy writing?

466
00:32:26,775 --> 00:32:28,035
Does it look like I enjoy it?

467
00:32:28,175 --> 00:32:29,935
You do seem crazy about it.

468
00:32:30,275 --> 00:32:32,505
Is that an insult or a compliment?

469
00:32:34,135 --> 00:32:37,375
Why do you write as if your life depends on it?

470
00:32:40,075 --> 00:32:42,105
"If I don't write to empty my mind,"

471
00:32:42,105 --> 00:32:43,675
"I go mad."

472
00:32:43,905 --> 00:32:44,975
- Lord Byron. - Lord Byron.

473
00:32:47,675 --> 00:32:50,105
It looks like you read a lot.

474
00:32:50,735 --> 00:32:54,535
Life can be tough, you know. Books are the only things that console me.

475
00:32:55,135 --> 00:32:59,235
This world can be ridiculous. I feel the same way with writing.

476
00:32:59,705 --> 00:33:01,605
Has your life been tough?

477
00:33:03,035 --> 00:33:04,605
It still is.

478
00:33:06,405 --> 00:33:08,675
Did you decide to write a novel as a way of overcoming it?

479
00:33:08,675 --> 00:33:12,145
For a desperate attempt, it looks pretty cool.

480
00:33:13,035 --> 00:33:16,105
Compared to holding hands with someone who might betray me,

481
00:33:16,505 --> 00:33:17,775
it's safer.

482
00:33:17,775 --> 00:33:19,735
I can be as desperate as I want and not look pitiful.

483
00:33:19,735 --> 00:33:21,935
It also allows me to escape the reality without drugs.

484
00:33:21,935 --> 00:33:25,175
And if I'm lucky, it can be a lucrative career.

485
00:33:26,375 --> 00:33:27,645
Is it worth all the work?

486
00:33:27,645 --> 00:33:29,075
Well, I think so.

487
00:33:29,675 --> 00:33:33,605
But I'd be happier if I could earn a living through it.

488
00:33:34,205 --> 00:33:36,375
What kind of writer do you want to become?

489
00:33:36,875 --> 00:33:38,575
A writer who's original.

490
00:33:39,875 --> 00:33:41,675
A writer whom no one copies?

491
00:33:42,105 --> 00:33:43,105
No.

492
00:33:43,605 --> 00:33:46,145
A writer whom no one can copy.

493
00:33:46,435 --> 00:33:47,605
- Chateaubriand. - Chateaubriand.

494
00:33:49,275 --> 00:33:51,035
You're really good at making up stories.

495
00:33:51,875 --> 00:33:54,575
I'm not making anything up. It actually happened.

496
00:33:54,575 --> 00:33:57,645
I smiled? 10 years ago?

497
00:33:58,645 --> 00:34:00,775
There's no way I smiled back then.

498
00:34:02,145 --> 00:34:04,205
What happened to you back then?

499
00:34:05,175 --> 00:34:06,975
I don't like to earn pity through telling my life stories.

500
00:34:08,935 --> 00:34:13,175
So something did happen, and you do have some stories to tell.

501
00:34:14,435 --> 00:34:16,005
Let's get going if you're done.

502
00:34:17,875 --> 00:34:19,435
It was phenomenal.

503
00:34:20,905 --> 00:34:22,775
The novel on the piece of paper you threw away.

504
00:34:23,705 --> 00:34:26,775
It was better than any novel you've written so far.

505
00:34:28,505 --> 00:34:30,775
I already knew it back then.

506
00:34:31,035 --> 00:34:34,005
I thought, "He's going to become a very successful writer."

507
00:34:36,935 --> 00:34:38,775
I've been rooting for you since then.

508
00:34:39,505 --> 00:34:42,035
"I hope that desperate attempt turns into something solid."

509
00:34:42,435 --> 00:34:45,005
"I hope he can soon make a living through writing alone."

510
00:34:46,105 --> 00:34:48,805
And I prayed for you.

511
00:34:49,905 --> 00:34:53,275
"I hope his tough life doesn't stall him."

512
00:34:54,005 --> 00:34:56,675
I hoped that it'd just be a fleeting ordeal you had to go through...

513
00:34:56,675 --> 00:34:58,735
to be groomed into a phenomenal writer.

514
00:34:59,805 --> 00:35:01,775
I hoped that all the suffering...

515
00:35:02,205 --> 00:35:04,535
would just be a training process for you.

516
00:35:11,035 --> 00:35:12,735
It's been 10 years, so I'd like to ask you this.

517
00:35:14,645 --> 00:35:16,375
Are you now able to make a living through writing?

518
00:35:19,675 --> 00:35:22,705
Of course. I've achieved much more than that.

519
00:35:23,335 --> 00:35:25,605
I've bought a mansion, a deer,

520
00:35:25,605 --> 00:35:27,205
and a car. I can buy whatever I want.

521
00:35:29,505 --> 00:35:31,575
Then have you become a writer whom no one can copy?

522
00:35:32,235 --> 00:35:36,435
As you can see, I'm Mr. Han Se Ju's...

523
00:35:36,435 --> 00:35:39,605
ghost writer, Yoo Jin Oh.

524
00:35:46,305 --> 00:35:49,035
I guess you don't think you've achieved it yet.

525
00:35:50,505 --> 00:35:51,505
Let's go.

